# Cursor Rules — SDRL Gravity Super-Resolution

## Project
Implementation of "Super-Resolution Reconstruction of Gravity Data Using
Semi-Supervised Dual Regression Learning" (Remote Sens. 2026, 18, 453).

## Stack
- Python 3.10+, PyTorch 2.1+
- Core library in `sdrl/`
- CLI entry points in `scripts/`
- Config files in `configs/` (YAML)

## Architecture (sdrl/model.py)
- **PrimaryNet**: LR→HR ×4, encoder-decoder with LiteMLA attention + RCAB blocks
  - Input: (B, 1, 50, 50)  Output: (B, 1, 200, 200)
  - Skip connections use F.interpolate for spatial alignment (not PixelShuffle)
- **DualNet**: HR→LR degradation, Input: (B, 1, 200, 200)  Output: (B, 1, 50, 50)
- Channel sizes: stem=32, enc1=64, enc2=128, enc3=256, bottleneck=256

## Loss (sdrl/loss.py)
- CompositeLoss: (1-α)·L1 + α·(1-SSIM), α is learnable, init=0.9
- SDRLLoss: Eq. 5 from paper — cycle + supervised + dual_reg + dual_cons terms
- Paired samples use all 4 terms; unpaired samples use only cycle term

## Data (sdrl/preprocess.py)
- Satellite: SSV33.1 NetCDF, 1′ resolution, global
- Shipborne: multiple .grd files (GMT format), ~15″ resolution
- Patches: LR=50×50, HR=200×200, stride=25 (50% overlap)
- QC: keep SSIM ∈ [0.2, 0.9] and RMSE < 0.4
- Memory-safe: process one .grd file at a time, never build global grid

## Conventions
- All patches normalised to [0, 1] before storing
- Saved as .npy: shape (N, 1, H, W)
- Configs loaded from YAML via `configs/` directory
- Checkpoints saved to `outputs/checkpoints/`
- Logs saved to `outputs/logs/`

## When modifying model.py
- ALWAYS check skip connection channel counts match decoder in_ch + skip_ch
- ALWAYS use F.interpolate(size=skip.shape[-2:]) not PixelShuffle for skip alignment
- Run tests/test_model.py after any architecture change

## When modifying loss.py
- Paired forward: pass both x and y to SDRLLoss.forward()
- Unpaired forward: pass y=None — only cycle loss is computed
- alpha is stored as logit internally, access via .alpha property

## Code style
- Type hints on all public functions
- Docstrings: one-line summary + Args/Returns for complex functions
- No bare except clauses
- Use pathlib.Path for file operations in scripts/
